# Retro Focus Areas

Copy this file to `FOCUS.md` in the same directory to customize retro analysis categories.
Edit the sections below to reflect your team's priorities. Add or remove categories as needed.

If a **Lint Rules** section is present, the retro will generate lint-rule tasks for
concrete, grep-detectable anti-patterns (max 3, actual mistakes only). Lint rules
are an action route, not a discovery category; first identify the underlying issue
in a category below.

---

## Category A: Tusk Workflow Failures

Failures, confusing behavior, missing safeguards, or broken handoffs in tusk itself
that should be filed as tusk issues.

## Category B: Context-Window Tangents

Issues noticed in the context that was pulled into the session, but unrelated to
the work just shipped. Bugs, tech debt, stale patterns, or architectural concerns
that should be addressed later.

## Category C: Task-Adjacent Follow-Up

Issues noticed in the context window that are related to the task or changed area,
but were not part of what just shipped. Adjacent edge cases, parity work,
secondary workflows, or deferred decisions that should be addressed later.

## Action Route: Lint Rules

Concrete, grep-detectable anti-patterns observed in this session (max 3).
Only include if an actual mistake occurred that a grep rule would catch.
Do NOT include general advice or style preferences.

## Analysis Lens: Debugging Velocity

If this was a bug or diagnosis task, ask what would have made it faster:
missing tests, logs, traces, commands, tusk safeguards, clearer handoffs, or docs.
Classify any resulting finding into Category A, B, C, or D.

## Category D: Project Documentation Updates

Project docs that should change because of what just shipped. Check whether changed
commands, config keys, workflows, schemas, prompt/skill behavior, install
behavior, user-facing output, or operational gotchas are reflected in
CLAUDE.md/AGENTS.md, README.md, docs/, .codex/prompts/, or distributed skills/.
